model.name: ArchiServices
model.documentation: This architecture introduces ArchiServices, a fictitous IT services company which will be used to illustrate the different features of the Torchlight document generation system. The example is based on ArchiSurance, the Archimate example model and a paper by Marco Vicente on Enterprise Architecture and IT Service Management.

element.name: Incident Management
element.documentation: The purpose of incident management is to restore normal service as quickly as possible and to minimise adverse impact on services.

element.name: Service Change Management
element.documentation: The purpose of change management is to control the lifecycle of all Changes. The primary objective of Service Change Management is to enable Changes to be made with the minimum disruption to IT services.

element.name: Problem Management
element.documentation: The purpose of problem management is to investigate the under lying cause of one or more incidents. It is most commonly used where there is a recurring trend of incidents with a likely shared root cause. The goal of this is to reduce overall incident volumes by fixing root causes.

element.name: Increased Client dependency on IT Systems
Lack of defined Service Management Processes to support SLA achievement
Immediate Client Business Impact from IT failure
Improve Co-ordination and the Processes that contribute to SLA Achievement
Increased Client Business Demand for 24x365 Services
Rapid Restoration of Services with minimal impact on Client Business Operations
Use ITSM processes
element.documentation: Use ITSM processes to identify, log, categorise, diagnose, solve and close incidents, problems and errors

element.name: Use Service Desk to Manage ITSM Processes
element.documentation: Use Service Desk function to managed ITSM processes for incidents, problems, service requests from users

element.name: Managed technical Team via ITSM
element.documentation: Use ITSM process to manage co-ordination betweeen application and infrastructure teams in resolution of incidents an problems.

element.name: Service Desk and ITSM Capability Implementation
Client Locations Nationwide
element.documentation: Client locations are managed by the Mobile Engineering function who provide support for local client devices, infrastructure and applications.

element.name: ArchiServices London Office
element.documentation: ArchiServices London Office handles incidents and requests from clients, via a Customer Support function There is also a team for Application Service Support to aid incident resolution and recovery. Service Management handles requests for change, reporting, problems and SLA management.

element.name: Disaster Recovery Warrington
element.documentation: This location is used to provide remote backup of data from the main data centre in Stevenage

element.name: ArchiServices Stevenage Data Center
element.documentation: ArchiService data centre holds the client infrastructure and applications, plus the supporting infrastructure and application used to support the clients infrastructure. The Infrastructure services team is located there and provides remote infrastructure support and dispatches the mobile engineers.

view.name: AS01 Organisation Structure
view.documentation: The ArchiServices organisation has a board of Administration, Product, Sales, and Operations departments. These are supported by Quality, Finance and HR functions. The services are delivered by the Operations department and our solution architecture will focus on these elements.

view.name: AS02 Operations Services Structure
view.documentation: This unit has a director and four teams: Service Management, Customer Management and supporting units for Infrastructure and Applications. These teams enact four support functions providing Customer Support, Remote Infrastructure Support, Application Support, and Mobile Engineering.

view.name: AS03 Service Delivery Structure
view.documentation: ArchiServices operation are spread across a number of locations.

view.name: DG01 Drivers and Goals
view.documentation: ArchiService desire for improvement is based on two key drivers a) Increase dependency by its customers on IT systems b) Desired for improved availability. This leads to two key goals for this solution - need to improve processes and co-ordination between processes; need for rapid restoration of services with minimal impact on the clients business.

view.name: Contents
view.documentation: The solution architecture is divided into four sections, covering requirements, as-is, to-be and transition implementation.

node.label: To-be model of ArchiServices
node.documentation: This defines the new To-be solution that will implement new ITSM processes.

view.name: TB02 Target Business Architecture
view.documentation: A Service Desk Business Function is introduced, alongside the implementation of three ITSM processes for Problem, Incident and Change management These will form part of the existing support functions.

view.name: TB01 ITSM Requirement Realisation
view.documentation: The two goals for the new service solution have been refined further into three requirements.

view.name: TB03 Target Operational Services Structure
view.documentation: The new Service Desk function will be assigned to Customer Services Function and expanded to support the new functions.

view.name: TB04 Target IT Architecture
view.documentation: The new ITSM processes will be realised by the Introduction of a Service Desk Application. The application will be used by the support functions.

view.name: TB05 Target Service Delivery Structure
view.documentation: The implementation of the new ITSM process will introduce a Service Desk function in London offices and New Service Desk Application into the Stevenage Data Centre. A transition project will be required to implement these.

view.name: T01 Transition Implementation
view.documentation: The service transition will consist of two workpackages to implement the new Service Desk architecture and the ITSM Processes. These will realise the to-be architecture and implement two new capabilities that will meet the goals for rapid restoration of services and improved co-ordination.
